</div></div><header><time pubdate datetime="2013-06-18T11:09:28-04:00"><div class="time_status">Updated</div><div class="day">18</div><div class="month">Jun</div><div class="year">2013</div><div class="time">11:09am, EDT</div></time><h1 class="gl_headline">'Day of honor': Afghans take over national security from US-led forces</h1></header><div class="postBody"><div class="postText"><div class="vine-p p-content_ArticleText clearfix"><div class="articleText"><div id="vine-inlineVideo__19022440" class="inlineVideo  photo_align_block" data-contentid="19022440"><iframe videoId="" thumbnail="http://msnbcmedia.msn.com/j/MSNBC/Components/Photo/_new/a_3k_brown_afghan_130618.thumb.jpg" src="http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/39788177?launch=52240367&amp;csid=NBC_News_Roll_Up&amp;&amp;&height=429&width=600" height="439" width="600"  border="0" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" hspace="0" vspace="0"></iframe><p>A deadly explosion in Kabul claimed three lives and injured dozens while, in another part of the city, US-led NATO troops handed control to Afghanistan's local forces. NBCNews.com's Dara Brown reports.</p><!-- end19022440 --></div><div class="byline">By Akbar Shinwari and Sohel Uddin, NBC News</div><p>KABUL, Afghanistan &ndash; U.S.-led troops handed complete control of security to Afghanistan authorities Tuesday &ndash; an act of faith in country&rsquo;s fledgling police and army in the face of near-constant insurgent attacks.</p><p>The formal transfer of responsibility is major milestone in the process of withdrawal from the country, 12 years after&nbsp;<a target="_blank" href="http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_87183.htm">NATO-led mission ISAF began its mission to end Taliban rule</a>.</p><p>However, a botched car bomb that killed at least three civilians just before the official handover ceremony raising renewed questions about how the country&rsquo;s 352,000-strong security forces will tackle the militant threat.</p>
